<chapter xml:id="ch_vectors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Vectors</title>
<introduction>
    <p>
Vector analysis is an important aspect of quantifying motion that occurs in more than one physical dimension. Driving a car on a flat surface is an example of motion in two dimensions, whereas, flying a plane through the air is an example of three-dimensional motion.
    </p>
    
    <p> 
You will begin your study of physics by gaining a foundational understanding of what vectors are and how to represent them visually and mathematically. 
    </p>

    </introduction>
		
    <objectives>
      
      <introduction><p>After successful completion of this chapter, you will be able to:</p></introduction>

 <ol>
<li><p>Explain the difference between a vector and a scalar</p></li>
<li><p>List common vectors and scalars</p></li>
<li><p>Represent vectors using multiple representations (diagrams, graphs, words, equations)</p></li>
<li><p>Resolve a vector into components</p></li>
<li><p>Define and use unit vector notation</p></li>
<li><p>Add and subtract vectors graphically and mathematically</p></li>
<li><p>Multiply a vector by a scalar quantity</p></li>
<li><p>Move between the component representation and the magnitude and direction angle representation of vectors. </p></li>
<li><p>Determine position and displacement vectors</p></li>
<li><p>Construct scientific explanations and reasoning</p></li>
<!--
<li><p>Take the dot product between two vectors</p></li>
-->
</ol>


</objectives>

    


      
  
